WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:04.517
So as I said, they do relative position encoding.

00:04.537 --> 00:05.198
What does that mean?

00:05.658 --> 00:13.648
So that means that the position encoding depends on where you look from.

00:13.989 --> 00:18.435
So what I've drawn at the beginning, like this here, this isn't entirely correct.

00:19.376 --> 00:21.439
You have to look at each token individually.

00:21.499 --> 00:24.182
So for this middle token here, for example,

00:24.162 --> 00:26.225
The positions look like this.

00:26.285 --> 00:29.430
They look like negative 2, negative 1, 0, 1, 2.

00:29.791 --> 00:40.247
And you would have kind of a table, not with absolute positions, but you'd actually have a table with negative 2, negative 1, 0, plus 1, plus 2, and so on.

00:40.787 --> 00:42.210
And you would retrieve those vectors.

00:42.270 --> 00:47.398
And then when you consider the next vector, this one right here, it would look different.

00:47.698 --> 00:51.604
It would write this would be 0, this minus 1, minus 2, and so on.

00:51.584 --> 00:53.506
So they do two things.

00:53.686 --> 00:55.528
First of all, they truncate at some point.

00:56.188 --> 00:58.250
They simply say, well, our context window is two.

00:58.711 --> 01:03.415
So instead of going negative three here, we simply keep it at negative two.

01:03.515 --> 01:07.279
So everything beyond negative two gets also the vector for negative two.

01:07.359 --> 01:13.805
So that vector here is going to be just plugged into here and into here for this token.

01:14.606 --> 01:21.372
And for this token, for the previous token, it is only going to be plugged here.

01:21.352 --> 01:21.993
nowhere else.

01:22.974 --> 01:27.559
There are ways to efficiently implement this, and that's this algorithm right here.

01:27.939 --> 01:36.909
Don't want to go too much into it, but just so you're aware, you don't have to consider each token really individually during it attention.

01:36.990 --> 01:39.112
That would be prohibitively expensive.

01:39.212 --> 01:49.063
So you can do one big matrix multiply and then sort of pick and choose together from your, from the matrix that results, especially with this truncation.

01:49.644 --> 01:50.785
This is this algorithm.

01:52.182 --> 01:54.044
So they call it efficient implementation.

01:55.004 --> 02:02.491
All right, so that is this position enhanced or disentangled information.

02:02.551 --> 02:03.912
Why is it disentangled again?

02:04.332 --> 02:07.975
Because in every layer, they have a side input.

02:08.255 --> 02:16.442
This piece right here is the side input that they sort of feed on top of this information.

02:16.963 --> 02:21.987
And they specifically construct the attention matrix out of the three things.

02:21.967 --> 02:23.851
It's almost like two contributions.

02:23.891 --> 02:27.700
The one contribution is, hey, let's feed in position information in each layer.

02:28.001 --> 02:30.165
And I think that has been tried before.

02:30.226 --> 02:31.027
That's pretty simple.

02:31.067 --> 02:48.507
But then the second thing is that we don't simply add the two vectors when we input it into the attention, but we're going to construct basically three attention matrices and then add those together once we determine the inner products between each of those.

02:48.787 --> 02:50.050
Okay.

